  <h1>About This Recipe Application</h1>

  <p>
    This application was built using Ruby on Rails as part of a full-stack web development project.
    It demonstrates database design, data integration from multiple sources, and ActiveRecord associations.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>📊 Data Sources</h2>

  <p>This application uses multiple data sources as required:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>TheMealDB API (Categories)</strong><br>
      https://www.themealdb.com/api/json/v1/1/list.php?c=list
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>TheMealDB API (Areas)</strong><br>
      https://www.themealdb.com/api/json/v1/1/list.php?a=list
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>TheMealDB API (Ingredients)</strong><br>
      https://www.themealdb.com/api/json/v1/1/list.php?i=list
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>TheMealDB API (Recipes / Meals)</strong><br>
      https://www.themealdb.com/api/json/v1/1/search.php?s=
    </li>

    <li>
      <strong>Faker Gem</strong><br>
      Used to generate random tags for recipes
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These sources provide structured data that is stored in a relational database using ActiveRecord models.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>🗄️ Database Structure (ERD Overview)</h2>

  <p>
    The application uses a relational database with the following main entities:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Recipes</strong> – central table containing meal information</li>
    <li><strong>Categories</strong> – classification of recipes</li>
    <li><strong>Areas</strong> – region or origin of recipes</li>
    <li><strong>Ingredients</strong> – list of ingredients</li>
    <li><strong>Tags</strong> – labels generated using Faker</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Relationships:</strong></p>

  <ul>
    <li>A Recipe belongs to a Category and an Area</li>
    <li>A Recipe has many Ingredients (through RecipeIngredients)</li>
    <li>A Recipe has many Tags (through RecipeTags)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Join tables (<em>RecipeIngredients</em> and <em>RecipeTags</em>) are used to implement many-to-many relationships.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>⚙️ Technologies Used</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Ruby on Rails</li>
    <li>ActiveRecord ORM</li>
    <li>SQLite Database</li>
    <li>REST APIs</li>
  </ul>

